{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WeMpuxR6CLBdkp9uMsQ7MS","type":"tool_result","content":"165\t\n166\t    All units must be in the canonical format produced by\n167\t    ``definitions.cases.normalize_precondition_units``. No format\n168\t    detection or legacy field handling is performed here; the legacy\n169\t    execution branch from ``run_flow.py`` is not carried forward.\n170\t\n171\t    For each unit, the probe tests whether the target state already holds:\n172\t\n173\t    * probe **passes** -> state already present, apply is skipped.\n174\t    * probe **fails** + ``on_probe_fail=\"skip\"`` (the default, used by setup\n175\t      units) -> the \"not yet present\" signal is expected, so apply runs to\n176\t      establish the state, then verify.\n177\t    * probe **fails** + ``on_probe_fail=\"error\"`` -> a readiness/convergence\n178\t      gate the apply cannot satisfy. The probe is retried up to\n179\t      ``verify_retries`` times (``verify_interval_sec`` apart) to let a slow\n180\t      cluster converge; the failure becomes fatal only after that budget.\n181\t\n182\t    Retries verify up to ``verify_retries`` times with\n183\t    ``verify_interval_sec`` between attempts. All command output is\n184\t    appended to *log_path*.\n185\t\n186\t    ``phase_timeout_sec`` bounds the wall-clock time of the whole phase\n187\t    (``None`` = unbounded, the default for callers that do not opt in).\n188\t    When set, each command's timeout is capped to the remaining budget and\n189\t    the phase aborts as soon as the deadline passes -- this is what makes\n190\t    ``--setup-timeout`` (``settings.precondition_timeout_sec``) actually\n191\t    bound the precondition phase, mirroring the oracle's wall-clock cap.\n192\t\n193\t    Returns\n194\t    -------\n195\t    dict\n196\t        Keys: ``ok`` (bool), ``units`` (list[dict] of per-unit outcomes),\n197\t        ``output`` (str), ``timed_out`` (bool -- True if the phase budget\n198\t        was exhausted).\n199\t    \"\"\"\n200\t    import os\n201\t    import subprocess\n202\t\n203\t    log_path.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)\n204\t    env = {**os.environ, **role_bindings, **(env_vars or {})}\n205\t    all_output: list[str] = []\n206\t    unit_outcomes: list[dict[str, Any]] = []\n207\t    overall_ok = True\n208\t\n209\t    # Wall-clock deadline for the whole phase. ``None`` means unbounded.\n210\t    deadline = (time.monotonic() + phase_timeout_sec) if phase_timeout_sec else None\n211\t    timed_out = False\n212\t\n213\t    def _exec(cmd_entry: dict[str, Any], phase: str, unit_id: str):\n214\t        \"\"\"Run one command, capping its timeout to the remaining phase budget."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5a6c058b-b8a5-4cef-aeaf-7999e1cdd491","uuid":"ebdfb7f6-83dc-4c73-b148-470523a75f72","timestamp":"2026-07-03T13:29:22.782Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/mydata/karma/karma/runtime/case.py","content":"\n    All units must be in the canonical format produced by\n    ``definitions.cases.normalize_precondition_units``. No format\n    detection or legacy field handling is performed here; the legacy\n    execution branch from ``run_flow.py`` is not carried forward.\n\n    For each unit, the probe tests whether the target state already holds:\n\n    * probe **passes** -> state already present, apply is skipped.\n    * probe **fails** + ``on_probe_fail=\"skip\"`` (the default, used by setup\n      units) -> the \"not yet present\" signal is expected, so apply runs to\n      establish the state, then verify.\n    * probe **fails** + ``on_probe_fail=\"error\"`` -> a readiness/convergence\n      gate the apply cannot satisfy. The probe is retried up to\n      ``verify_retries`` times (``verify_interval_sec`` apart) to let a slow\n      cluster converge; the failure becomes fatal only after that budget.\n\n    Retries verify up to ``verify_retries`` times with\n    ``verify_interval_sec`` between attempts. A